.TH read 1 "April 1993" "Scilab Group" "Scilab Function"
.so man1/sci.an
.SH NAME
read - matrices read
.SH CALLING SEQUENCE
.nf
[x]=read(file-name,m,n,[format])   
[x]=read(file-name,m,n,k,format)
.fi
.SH PARAMETERS
.TP 10
file-name
: string or integer (logical unit number)
.TP 10
m, n
: integers (dimensions of the matrix x). Set m=-1 if you dont know the
numbers of rows, so the whole file is read.
.TP 10
format
: string (fortran format). If format='(a)' then read reads a vector of strings
n must be equal to 1.
.TP 10
k
: integer
.SH DESCRIPTION
reads row after row
the \fVmxn\fR matrix \fVx\fR (\fVn=1\fR for character chain) in the file \fVfile-name\fR (string or integer).
.LP
Two examples for \fVformat\fR are : \fV(1x,e10.3,5x,3(f3.0))\fR,\fV(10x,a20)\fR 
( the default value is \fV*\fR).
.LP
The type of the result will depend on the specified form. 
If form is numeric \fV(d,e,f,g)\fR the matrix will be a scalar matrix and if form
contains the character \fVa\fR the matrix will be a matrix of character strings.
.LP
A direct access file can be used if using the parameter \fVk\fR which is 
is the vector of record numbers to be read (one record per row),
thus \fVm\fR must be \fVm=prod(size(k))\fR.
.LP
To read on the keyboard use \fVread(%io(2),...)\fR.
.SH EXAMPLE
.nf
A=rand(3,5); write('foo',A);
B=read('foo',3,5)
B=read('foo',-1,5)
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
file, readb, write, %io

